Exploratory data analysis¶

Exploratory data analysis is the method of examining data and extracting findings. It's fiction, a storyline that data is attempting to convey. EDA is a way of analyzing data using a variety of tools and graphical approaches such as matplotlib, charts, heatmap, scatterplots and seaborn.The first phase in the data modelling process is often EDA.

Univariate analysis¶

Uni stands for "one," meaning that there is just one sort of variable in the data. Univariate analysis' main purpose is to characterise the data. The information will be collected, analysed, and a pattern will be identified. Univariate analysis can be carried out in a number of methods, the most of which are descriptive. Frequency Polygons, Histograms, and Bar Charts are all examples of frequency distribution tables.

In [8]:
#using seaborn library to plot distribution plot and dropping null values
sns.distplot(data['Income'].dropna());
plt.title("Income distribution plot")
Out[8]:
Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Income distribution plot')

Most of the data found between 20 and 100 customers having higher ratio of Income is less than normal

Inferences from Univariate Analysis :
Average age group of customers is 45yrs
Average Experience of customers is 20
Most of the customers are of age group 55
There are no null values in the data
75% of the family members of the customer are 3
75% of the customers are using Online banking facility.
Majority of the Customers are with experience between 20-30yrs
Outliers are present in Mortgage and Income feature
Income and Mortgage are right skewed
CCAVG , Mortgage, Personal Loan, Securities Account, CD Account are highly skewed
Mortgage is extremly positive squared
There are negative values in the Experience Columns which is impossible imputation is required on it.

Bivariate Analysis¶

Bivariate Analysis means 2. Comparsion of two variables to illustarte some meaningful information is bivariate analysis.
It can be heatmaps,scatterplots, histograms,line-plots

  • Seaborn's lmplot is a 2D scatterplot with an optional overlaid regression line. This is useful for comparing numeric variables.
  • Logistic regression for binary classification is also supported with lmplot

In data science, model evaluation is critical. It assists you in comprehending your model's performance and makes it simple to exhibit your model to others. There are numerous evaluation metrics available, but only a few of them are adequate for regression.
The metrics that are best and we are using are :

  • Mean square error
  • Root Mean square error
  • Accuracy Score

Though we have a very good accuracy score of 91%, Precision (True Positive Rate) means out of customers who we predicted to buy the loan how many actually bought the loan which is 84%. As said above, the extent of Class Imbalance is higher in our data. How are we going to ensure our model does not make biased decisions? There are couple of ways to achieve this and this technique is called resampling

Improvement of logistic regression¶

In [44]:
#resampling the target variable
from  sklearn.utils import resample
df_majority=data[data['Personal_Loan']==0]
df_minority=data[data['Personal_Loan']==1]
df_upsample_minority=resample(df_minority,replace=True,random_state=12,n_samples=4520)
df_upsample=pd.concat([df_majority,df_upsample_minority])
count=df_upsample['Personal_Loan'].value_counts()
count.plot(kind='bar',figsize=(5,5));

Now imbalanced has been changed.Both classes for our dependent variable are same and have less unsampled data which we can ignore. Now we are going to apply logistic regression again to sampled and unsampled data to see the variations of the data and results

In [45]:
X_upsampled=df_upsample.drop(['Personal_Loan'],axis=1)

##on the whole data
train_accuracy, test_accuracy=[],[]

for j in alphas:
    tree= DecisionTreeClassifier(ccp_alpha=j)
    tree.fit(X_train,y_train)
    ytrain_pred=tree.predict(X_train)
    ytest_pred=tree.predict(X_test)
    train_accuracy.append(accuracy_score(y_train, ytrain_pred))
    test_accuracy.append(accuracy_score(y_test, ytest_pred))

sns.set()
plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
sns.lineplot(y=train_accuracy, x=alphas, label='Training Accuracy')
sns.lineplot(y=test_accuracy, x=alphas, label='Testing Accuracy')
plt.xlabel("Alpha values")
plt.ylabel("Training")
plt.title("Alpha and recall for training and testing")
plt.show()

From the above plot, we can see that between alpha=0.01 and 0.02, we get the maximum test accuracy. Although our train accuracy has decreased from 0.012, our model is now more generalized and it will perform better on unseen data.

Conclusions¶

We got the dataset about personal loan which includes customers important features highlighting income, Age, Education. We perform EDA on our dataset and find few important patterns from it. After evaluating two different ML algoirthms we can predict that:

  • Customers having education will buy personal loan
  • Customers that have higher income will buy personal loan
    Management should focus on education as well as income of the customers to extract results about personal loan borrow

Recommendations¶

The bank instead of calling someone for purchasing a loan should focus on the key features like Education of the customer, Income of the customer, total family members, and CCAVG of the customer.
It seems that customers who have higher education level and with above average income have the higher proportion to purchase the personal loan.
Clients with these characteristics should be targeted in the Business Plan to increase their access to Personal Loans.
The bank can expand its reach outside its existing customer base. Consumers who match the criteria in its service area and beyond detected as a result of our predictive modelling.
